Life on the edge!
We hope that Jeff, Jeri, Atlas, and their fur babies NEVER need our products, but they have them “just in case” !

from @thisisironclad

Giving fear the middle finger.

In this episode, meet Jeff, a former Navy SEAL, and his wife, Jeri, a physician assistant, who move to Alaska to start a new life on their own homestead. 

Along with their team of sled dogs, Jeff and Jeri embark on a journey north of the Arctic Circle in pursuit of the Porcupine caribou herd to try and fill the freezer for the year.

New episodes every week.

node.text: Whether negligence is involved, or just a freak accident, we all know anything can happen on the water. The question is, will you be prepared to save a life? Could be an accident on your boat, a situation 50 miles offshore, or a problem that you just so happened to be first on the scene. Will you be ready? It’s something as mariners we all don’t think about as much as we should, and I’m here to raise awareness so you as the captain will be ready to save a life. We teamed up with @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help provide all captains with the best and most affordable Qualified Captain Trauma Kit. It is specifically dialed in with the medical equipment you will need for when things go south. I treat these kits like an EPIRB. I don’t leave with out one whether it’s my boat, a friends boat, or a commercial boat. More information about the kits are on our website. Go check them out today, and always be prepared. Thank you @djstruntz @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help make this happen. At the end of the day, we all want to have a good time and make it home safe. Have a great week everyone. #qualified #qualifiedcaptaintraumakits #beprepared #savealife #northamericanrescue #pelicancase #collobration

node.text:
First Responder Training by @nardoctor 
Inter-War period begins (for most) NOW. It is our responsibility to make sure everyone is trained to be a first responder. Do not forget these training lessons learned from the JTS AAR review from @thepitdoc, @traumadaddy, @max.dodge83, and @prolonged_field_care in their Summer @jsomonline article “An Analysis of Prehospital Trauma Registry After-Action Reviews in Afghanistan”. Here are some painful comments that are totally preventable. 
.
@deployedmedicine(www.depployedmedicine.com): What to teach to each level, how to teach it, standards, videos, skills assessment sheets are all available to everyone for free. This info was decided on and reviewed by the @tc3committee. Use this as a reference or as a complete teaching package. 
.
If you are military (non-medic), make sure you master Tier 1 (TC3 All Service Members, First Responder, etc..) and then look for opportunity to advance to Tier 2 (Combat Life Saver). If you are a medic/provider ensure every single member of your unit is qualified and current on these two levels. Integrate the skills and capabilities into all training, not just designated medical training time. Keep your aid bag/IFAKs with you, expired/re-used class 8 and train first responders at every opportunity (you won’t have time for this “later”). 
.
If you are a civilian novice and don’t have someone to teach you, consider starting with a bleeding control course as this will give you the basics of tourniquet application and wound packing. There are several advanced first responder courses to choose from there, check out nartraining.com for online and in person courses. Consider adding in a wilderness medicine course (@wildmedsociety) for remote/improvised care. If that all goes well, consider a formal course like EMT-B to lead you into a career of medicine. 

#tccc #tecc #training #beprepared #emergencymedicine #tacmed #nardoctor

Hope 🙏🏼🇺🇸❤️

from @havokjournal
•
An open letter to the newborn daughter of Marine Corps Lance Cpl. Rylee McCollum

Dear little one,

Welcome to the world! We’ve been waiting for you!

I just saw Wyoming Senator John Barrasso announce your big day on the floor of the United States Senate. 

You are beautiful.

I know you have no idea who I am nor Senator Barrasso.  Heck, right now, none of this is even relevant.

But I want you to know that the State of Wyoming, the birthplace of your daddy, is granting you honorary citizenship. 

While our collective hearts hurt that your daddy was taken away from you, you need to know that you gained over 500,000 relatives.  And while the majority of us didn’t know your namesake, we hold him dear to our hearts.

Your daddy was a hero. And each of us here in Wyoming is grateful that he shared this state with us even though we believe his time was way too short. 

His legacy will live on.

It will live through us, his (and now your) extended family here in Wyoming. 

You don’t know us now but my promise is to you that if you ever need us, we will be there.  If you see someone with a bucking horse on their shirt, hat, license plate, ask them where they were on August 26, 2021.  If they tell you Wyoming and you tell them what your daddy’s name was, I guarantee you they will move heaven and earth to help you.

Because we owe your daddy.  He laid his life down to protect us.  He reached his hand out to help strangers, no questions asked. 

And I promise you, we will return the favor.

Because that is who he was and honestly, that is who we are.

God has blessed this little place we call home.  And now, He has blessed the world again.

Welcome, little one. 

And rest in peace, Daddy Rylee.  We got this. 

“Some people spend an entire lifetime wondering if they made a difference in the world. But, the Marines don't have that problem.”
― Ronald Reagan

Never above you.
Never below you. 
Always beside you.

Author: unknown

node.text:
Keep’em warm!!!
from @the_resuscitationist
•
TEAM,

We have to get better about keeping our trauma patients warm. It's the culmination of multiple key steps/interventions that give our patients the best chance of survival.

HYPOTHERMIA: 
-->is frequently overlooked and underappreciated. Prevention and mitigation begins at point of injury  and part of the MARCH algorithms. Notice the slides that I discuss common locations of heat loss, the impact and treatment approaches.

PICTURE:
--> even in an warm environment, the care giver is correctly not being cognitively biased and still keeping the patient warm with external commerical heating units/blankets. 

EMS: 
-->warm IV fluids, warm the ambulance, cover the patient (especially if prolonged extraction, down time or cold environments).

PROTIP:
--> many commercial heating units do take time to activate, and especially at high elevations. Consider opening them up prior to a mission or prior to arrival/receiving of the patient.

TASKER: 
-->with multiple people, the team lead can designate another individual to cover down on treatments. When team lead works through their assessment/interventions and moves the heating elements, the tasker can assist with lowering "task saturation" and covering up where the primary care giver moved on. 

NOTE: for giving blood products, I recognize that sometime heating elements don't optimally work or theres technical issues. If there needs to be a choice between cold blood and no blood, give the cold blood products. Just be aware and make those aggressive hypothermia prevention measures.

STEPS:
Stop the bleed--> Complete MARCH-->Give blood-->Give calcium/txa/abx/pain control-->warm the patient--> secondary survey/ reassessment.

Hypothermia->kills trauma patients.
